We assume a linear relationship between temperature and length: $L = c dot T$.
  The temperature at the triple point is $T_"TP" = 273.16 " K"$, where $L_"TP" = 5.0 " cm"$.
  
  The difference between the ice point and the triple point is $Delta T = 273.16 " K" - 273.15 " K" = 0.01 " K"$. The corresponding change in length is:
  $ Delta L = c dot Delta T = L_"TP" / T_"TP" dot Delta T = (5 " cm") / (273.16 " K") times 0.01 " K" = 0.00018 " cm" $
  
  Since the measurement uncertainty of the instrument is $0.01 " cm"$, this tiny difference ($0.00018 " cm"$) *cannot* be resolved or measured with this thermometer.